    <id>https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.13406</id>
    <title>Repo over the Financial Crisis</title>
    <updated>2025-02-10T00:00:00+00:00</updated>
    <author>
      <name>ADAM COPELAND, ANTOINE MARTIN</name>
    </author>
    <content>&lt;b&gt;The Journal of Finance&lt;/b&gt; &lt;br&gt;This paper uses new data to provide a comprehensive view of repo activity during the 2007 global financial crisis. We show that activity declined much more in the bilateral segment of the market than in the tri‐party segment. Surprisingly, a large share of the decline in activity is driven by repos backed by Treasury securities. Further, a disproportionate share of the decline in repo activity is connected to securities dealer's market‐making activity. In particular, the evidence suggests that at least part of the decline is not driven by clients pulling away from securities dealers because of counterparty credit concerns.</content>
    <link href="https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.13406"/>
    <category term="The Journal of Finance"/>
    <published>2025-02-10T00:00:00+00:00</published>
